type IntPointer own {
    ptr * int
}

func alloc_int() IntPointer
func load_int(ptr IntPointer) int
func store_int(ptr IntPointer, value int)
func free_int(ptr IntPointer)

i = alloc_int()
i.store_int(42)
i.free_int()


/*
Memory safety and concurrency safety do NOT depend on linear types
They are completely separate guarantees:

Guarantee	What provides it	Linear types needed?
No use-after-free	Move checker (mov)	No
No double-free	Move checker (mov)	No
No data races	Borrow checker (var exclusivity)	No
No buffer overflows	VRA + bounds checking	No
No dangling pointers	Borrow checker + unsafe gate	No
No resource leaks	Linear types	Yes
Linear types solve one specific problem: you cannot forget to clean up a resource. A leaked File handle is bad (you waste OS resources), but it doesn't cause a segfault or a data race. It's a correctness issue, not a safety issue.

So:

A user who never uses own/linear still writes memory-safe, concurrency-safe code
They might leak file handles or database connections — but the borrow checker and move semantics still protect them from UB
The standard library uses linear types to wrap system resources and prevent leaks
Users opt in when they have their own resource types
This is a strong argument for opt-in linearity. Making Point {x int, y int} linear by default adds friction without improving safety — a "leaked" Point is just a value on the stack that gets cleaned up automatically.

The safety layers are:


1. Type system          → no implicit conversions, no NULL
2. Borrow checker       → no aliased mutation (memory + concurrency safety)
3. Move semantics       → no use-after-free, no double-free
4. VRA / bounds check   → no buffer overflows
5. unsafe gate          → raw pointer ops quarantined
─── everything above: ALWAYS ON ───
6. Linear types (opt-in) → no resource leaks

*/